== Characteristics of Jōmon Period Earth-Pit Graves == # The diameter typically ranges from 0.7 to 1.5 meters. The pits are circular or square in shape, with circular forms being most common. # The depth is shallow relative to the surface area, with flat bottoms. # {{ill|Cover soil|ja|覆土 (考古学)|1=Overburden (archaeology)|lt=Overburden|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is usually backfilled manually in a single process. # While {{ill|human bones|ja|人骨|qq=draft|qq=draft}} are sometimes found, in many cases, no trace of them remains. # {{ill|Grave goods|ja|副葬品|qq=draft|qq=draft}} may accompany the burial. In the later and final phases of the period, the quality and quantity of such items increase, with many high-value crafted items being interred during the final phase.
Burial practices during the Jōmon period, inferred from human remains found in {{ill|shell middens|ja|貝塚|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, suggest that {{ill|flexed burial|ja|屈葬|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was common. The size and shape of the graves are thought to reflect this practice. Graves with {{ill|pebbles|ja|礫|qq=draft|qq=draft}} arranged inside or around the pits are specifically called '''Stone-Arranged Graves''' (配石墓).
Even when grave goods or human remains are absent, soil analyses, particularly of {{ill|fatty acid|ja|脂肪酸|qq=draft|qq=draft}} residues, can identify the structure as an earth-pit grave.
== Characteristics of Yayoi Period Earth-Pit Graves == The basic features remain similar to those of the Jōmon period, but new shapes, such as elliptical and rounded-rectangle forms, appear. With the increasing adoption of {{ill|extended burial|ja|伸展葬|qq=draft|qq=draft}} practices, rectangular-shaped pits become more prevalent in later periods. == See Also == * [[:en:Prehistoric storage pits|Earth Pit]] * {{ill|Flexed burial|ja|屈葬|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Wooden Coffin Graves|ja|木棺墓|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Jar Coffin Graves|ja|甕棺墓|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Stone Coffin Graves|ja|石棺墓|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Burial Practices of the Yayoi Period|ja|弥生時代の墓制|1=Funerary practices of the Yayoi period|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
