{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q10856121]] Wikidata name: hole-shaped grave [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 08:53, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} '''Earth-Pit Graves''' (土坑墓) refer to burial structures where {{ill|earth|ja|土砂|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/earth|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} is excavated to create a pit ([[:en:Prehistoric storage pits|Earth Pit]]) for interring human [[:en:corpse|remains]]. These graves were commonly used worldwide for [[:en:Burial|burial]] practices associated with {{ill|in-ground burials|ja|土葬|1=burial|lt=In-ground burials|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/in-ground burials|13=User:Immanuelle/burial|qq=}}, and in Japan, they were a prevalent form of graves during the [[:en:Jōmon period|Jōmon period]] to [[:en:Yayoi period|Yayoi period]]. In Japan, they are sometimes referred to as '''Earth Pits''' (土壙) or '''Earth-Pit Graves''' (土壙墓).
== Earth-Pit Graves of the Paleolithic Period == At the {{ill|Hasamiyama Site|ja|はさみ山遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hasamiyama Site|qq=}} in [[:en:Fujiidera|Fujidera, Osaka]], elliptical earth pits presumed to be graves have been identified.
== Characteristics of Jōmon Period Earth-Pit Graves == # The diameter typically ranges from 0.7 to 1.5 meters. The pits are circular or square in shape, with circular forms being most common. # The depth is shallow relative to the surface area, with flat bottoms. # {{ill|Cover soil|ja|覆土 (考古学)|1=Overburden (archaeology)|lt=Overburden|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cover soil|13=User:Immanuelle/Overburden (archaeology)|qq=}} is usually backfilled manually in a single process. # While {{ill|human bones|ja|人骨|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/human bones|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 人間の骨の一覧}} are sometimes found, in many cases, no trace of them remains. # [[:en:Grave goods|Grave goods]] may accompany the burial. In the later and final phases of the period, the quality and quantity of such items increase, with many high-value crafted items being interred during the final phase.
Burial practices during the Jōmon period, inferred from human remains found in [[:en:Midden|shell middens]], suggest that {{ill|flexed burial|ja|屈葬|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/flexed burial|qq=}} was common. The size and shape of the graves are thought to reflect this practice. Graves with [[:en:Pebble|pebbles]] arranged inside or around the pits are specifically called '''Stone-Arranged Graves''' (配石墓).
Even when grave goods or human remains are absent, soil analyses, particularly of [[:en:Fatty acid|fatty acid]] residues, can identify the structure as an earth-pit grave.
== Characteristics of Yayoi Period Earth-Pit Graves == The basic features remain similar to those of the Jōmon period, but new shapes, such as elliptical and rounded-rectangle forms, appear. With the increasing adoption of {{ill|Stretched burial|lt=Stretched burial|lt=Extended burial|ja|伸展葬|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/extended burial|qq=}} practices, rectangular-shaped pits become more prevalent in later periods. == See Also == * [[:en:Prehistoric storage pits|Earth Pit]] * {{ill|Flexed burial|ja|屈葬|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Flexed burial|qq=}} * {{ill|Wooden Coffin Graves|ja|木棺墓|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wooden Coffin Graves|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 弥生時代の墓制}} * [[:en:Jar burial|Jar burial]] * {{ill|Stone Coffin Graves|ja|石棺|1=Sekkan|qq=墓|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Stone Coffin Graves|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekkan|qq=}} * {{ill|Burial Practices of the Yayoi Period|ja|弥生時代の墓制|1=Funerary practices of the Yayoi period|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Burial Practices of the Yayoi Period|13=User:Immanuelle/Funerary practices of the Yayoi period|qq=}}
